cular formula enables calculation of relative molecular mass via summed atomic contributions. [Data: Entities (1162, 1177, 1161); Relationships (1571, 1607)]\\n\\nRELATIVE FORMULA MASS plays an analogous role for ionic/formula-unit substances (e.g., NaCl, CaCO3) and is used to state corresponding molar masses in g·mol⁻¹. This establishes a pipeline from composition → relative mass (unitless) → molar mass (with units), enabling mass–mole conversions. [Data: Entities (1190, 1186, 1188); Relationships (1650, 1642)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Exercises and question sets demonstrate applied stoichiometric routines\",\"explanation\":\"QUESTION 03: MOLE-BASED CALCULATIONS is explicitly described as asking learners to compute moles from mass, numbers of molecules from moles, and mass from moles, showing direct application of the n = m/M relationship and Avogadro-based conversions in routine problem solving. [Data: Entities (1219); Relationships (1678)]\\n\\nQUESTION 04: MOLES OF OXYGEN ATOMS IN COMPOUNDS focuses on structural counting within compounds (moles of oxygen atoms per mole of compound) and lists specific compounds including Al2O3 and Ba3(PO4)2. This extends the community from mass–mole conversions into formula-based atom counting per mole of compound. [Data: Entities (1220, 907, 1221); Relationships (1706, 1710)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Specific compounds serve as recurring worked examples for mass, moles, and formula-based reasoning\",\"explanation\":\"Several named substances are explicitly tied to molar-mass usage in examples. CARBON DIOXIDE is linked to a molar mass of 44 g·mol⁻¹, which is used to compute moles from a given mass (e.g., converting a 22 g sample using 44 g·mol⁻¹). [Data: Entities (220, 1188); Relationships (1638)]\\n\\nCALCIUM CARBONATE is similarly treated with a molar mass of 100 g·mol⁻¹, and it appears as a representative compound for applying relative formula mass to molar-mass statements. In addition, multiple organic and molecular examples (acetic acid, 